  "prompt": "Why do e-commerce companies offset last row results when paginating products?",
  "response": "When e-commerce companies paginate products, they often offset the last row results to ensure a smooth and consistent user experience. Here are some reasons why this practice is employed:\n\n1. **Seamless Browsing Experience**: Users expect a seamless browsing experience. By offsetting the last row and starting the next page with new products, users perceive continuous exploration without repetition of items, reducing frustration.\n\n2. **Accurate Data Representation**: Products in e-commerce often get added, removed, or updated frequently. Offset rows accommodate these changes by preventing duplicates or missing entries, ensuring accurate representation of product lists.\n\n3. **Performance Optimization**: Large datasets can be heavy on database performance. Pagination with offset rows helps to manage the load and improve performance, especially with high-volume queries, by reducing the amount of data processed at once.\n\n4. **Consistent User Navigation**: Offset last row results provide a consistent frame of reference for the user. When users navigate from one page to another, they expect to see a different subset of products, ensuring clear progression through the product inventory.\n\n5. **Preference and Relevance**: Some algorithms for product listing take user preferences, browsing history, or relevance into account. Offsetting prevents the same products from appearing repeatedly across pages, improving the algorithm\u2019s ability to display diverse and relevant options.\n\n6. **Dynamic Inventory Handling**: Inventory levels change dynamically due to sales and new arrivals. Offsetting handles these changes by smoothly transitioning products across pages without abrupt interruptions or duplications, reflecting real-time inventory accurately.\n\nBy offsetting last row results in paginated lists, e-commerce companies offer a well-organized, performant, and user-friendly product browsing experience, keeping users engaged and reducing the likelihood of encountering redundant or missing items.",
